  "prompt": "Is Mexican food in Mexico much hotter (spicier) than the Mexican food served in the United States?",
  "response": "The perception of spiciness in Mexican food can vary significantly between the cuisine served in Mexico and that found in the United States. In Mexico, traditional dishes may use a variety of chiles, many of which have nuanced flavors and varying levels of heat. While some foods can be quite spicy, others are not, and the spiciness often depends on regional preferences.\n\nIn the United States, Mexican cuisine is often adapted to suit a broader audience, sometimes resulting in milder dishes that cater to various palates. As a result, you might find that many Mexican restaurants in the U.S. serve foods that are less spicy than their authentic counterparts in Mexico. Additionally, American-style Mexican dishes may use less traditional ingredients and flavors, which can also affect the overall spice level.\n\nOverall, while there are many spicy dishes in both countries, authentic Mexican cuisine can sometimes be spicier on average than what is typically served in many U.S. restaurants.",
